## 1. One-Line Summary

- The Hook — A legendary benchmark for spin and control, Yasaka Rakza 7 proves that you don't need uncontrollable catapult to dominate the modern table tennis game.
- Archetype — Spin-Oriented Variable Attacker / All-Round Offensive.

## 2. Performance Analysis

- Speed & Gears
    - Passive Block Speed: Moderate and highly predictable; it doesn't jump off the racket prematurely.
    - Active Loop Speed: Good, but requires physical input. It will not bail you out with free speed if your footwork or weight transfer is lazy.
    - Linearity vs. Trampoline: Extremely linear. What you put in is exactly what you get out. The trampoline effect is very subdued compared to modern extreme-tension ESN rubbers.
    - Mid-Distance Carry: Adequate, but you will need to engage the sponge fully to maintain depth. It excels closer to the table.

- Spin Generation
    - Top-End Spin: Outstanding. The high proportion of natural gum in the topsheet provides incredible mechanical grip.
    - Opening Loop: Superb. Lifting heavy backspin with a slow, spinny loop is one of this rubber's greatest strengths.
    - Serve Quality: High. The lack of unwanted bounce allows for tight, heavily loaded short serves.

- Control & Short Game
    - Touch Play: Excellent. Pushes and drop shots are easy to keep low and short because the sponge isn't overly bouncy at low impacts.
    - Spin Sensitivity: Moderate. Because it is highly grippy, it does react to incoming spin, requiring proper racket angles.
    - Flick Window: Forgiving. The grip grabs the ball securely, giving you confidence to flick over the table.

- Throw Angle (Arc)
    - Trajectory: Medium-high.
    - Arc Behavior: Produces a pronounced arc with a very sharp dip at the end of the trajectory, making loops land safely on the table.

- Spin-Interaction Behavior
    - Against Heavy Topspin: Very stable, provided you actively close the angle. It doesn't slip.
    - Against Heavy Backspin: Excellent. The topsheet bites into the ball, making it very easy to generate the necessary lift.
    - Error Pattern: Missing short into the net if the player relies on the rubber to do the work, or overhitting if flattening out the stroke too much.

## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve
    - Generates massive spin with excellent short-placement control.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Very precise. The lack of extreme tensor-bounce prevents the ball from popping up.
    - Flick: Safe and spin-heavy, though not the fastest.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Works very well due to the high grip and medium-high throw, easily clearing the net.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Fantastic. It bites the ball perfectly for a high-spin, safe opening attack.
    - Continuous Looping: Highly consistent. The linear nature means your rhythm won't be disrupted by sudden power surges.
    - Power Loop / Kill: Good, but this is where it falls slightly short of modern ultra-fast rubbers. You need massive arm speed to hit clean winners.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: Stable and reliable, preferring a spin-oriented counter rather than a flat smash-counter.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Solid, but requires a firm forward stroke to penetrate the sponge.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Very safe. It absorbs pace nicely and doesn't shoot off the table.
    - Active Block: Excellent for directing the ball with precision into the corners.

- Smash & Flat Hit
    - Average. The medium-hard sponge and grippy topsheet are designed for spin, not flat driving. Flat hits can sometimes feel a bit sluggish.

- Defense
    - Chop: Surprisingly good for an offensive rubber due to the predictable bounce.
    - Lob: Easy to perform with heavy topspin, though it requires effort to get deep placement.

